[normal]9.
[normal]              
[normal]CCS is an integrated suite of te
[normal]chnologies 
[normal]which can
[normal] capture around 90 per cent of 
[normal]carbon dioxide 
[normal]emissions from large stationary sources
[normal] (typically power plants or large industrial installations) 
[normal]before it is emitted into the atmosphere. Captured 
[normal]carbon dioxide 
[normal]is then transported to se
[normal]lected site
[normal]s 
[normal]for permanent storage. The three major stages involved in CCS technology are: a) 
[normal]c
[normal]apture; b) 
[normal]t
[normal]ransport; and c) 
[normal]s
[normal]torage
[normal].
[normal]10.
[normal]              
[normal]Capture 
[normal]is the
[normal] separation of 
[normal]carbon dioxide
[normal] from other gases produced at large industrial process facilities
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]such as 
[normal](but not limited to) 
[normal]coal and natural gas power plants, oil
[normal] refineries, natural 
[normal]gas 
[normal]processing 
[normal]plants, steel mills and cement plants. Currently 
[normal]this can be achieved with three alternative technologies
[normal]: 
[normal]p
[normal]ost-combustion; 
[normal]p
[normal]re-combustion
[normal], and
[normal] 
[normal]o
[normal]xy-
[normal]combustion
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]f
[normal]or further details see: 
[normal]Florin &amp; Fennel, 2010
[normal]; MacDowell et al.
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]2010
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]11.
[normal]              
[normal]Transport
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] 
[normal]the transfer
[normal] 
[normal]of the 
[normal]captured 
[normal]carbon dioxide
[normal] 
[normal]from the CCS plant 
[normal]to a selected storage site
[normal], which 
[normal]may
[normal] 
[normal]be located several miles apart
[normal]. 
[normal]Transport can take place
[normal] 
[normal]via pipelines, either 
[normal]o
[normal]nshore 
[normal](
[normal]using 
[normal]a well-established technology 
[normal]already developed
[normal] 
[normal]for enhanced oil recovery) or offshore (currently 
[normal]the subject
[normal] 
[normal]of further research); or
[normal] 
[normal]via 
[normal]shipping 
[normal](
[normal]building on experience 
[normal]from the transport of
[normal] 
[normal]liquefied natural gas
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]1
[normal]2.
[normal]              
[normal]Storage
[normal] is the
[normal] permanent 
[normal]sequestration of 
[normal]carbon dioxide 
[normal]away from the atmosphere. 
[normal]Carbon dioxide 
[normal]is injected into porous rock, either aquifers containing salty water or depleted oil and gas reservoirs. 
[normal]In the UK, storage capacity in oil and gas fields 
[normal]could range from 7.4 to 9.
[normal]9 
[normal]billion tonnes of carbon dioxide. T
[normal]he storage 
[normal]potential
[normal] of saline fields is more uncertain, and could 
[normal]range from
[normal] 6.3 to 62.7 
[normal]billion tonnes of carbon dioxide
[normal] (for f
[normal]urther details 
[normal]see:
[normal] Blunt
[normal], 
[normal]2010
[normal]; Senior CCS Solutions Ltd, 2010
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]13.
[normal]              
[normal]Currently there are about 
[normal]20
[normal] CCS projects in operation
[normal] across the world
[normal], 
[normal]of which only
[normal] one is in Europe (the Sn
[normal]ø
[normal]hvit capture and storage project in Norway). 
[normal]Only eight of these projects
[normal] have been developed at 
[normal]full 
[normal]commercial scale
[normal] (EC, 2013)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.
[normal]              
[normal]An a
[normal]nalysis by 
[normal]the UK Energy Research Centre 
[normal](2013) 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]low-carbon 
[normal]electricity
[normal] potential review
[normal]ed
[normal] 
[normal]nine 
[normal]different scenarios 
[normal]which have been 
[normal]developed by 
[normal]a number of
[normal] institutions (
[normal]inclu
[normal]ding
[normal] the Committee on Climate Change, 
[normal]the Department of Energy and Climate Change 
[normal]and 
[normal]the UK Energy Research Centre)
[normal] 
[normal]to
[normal] model
[normal] 
[normal]ways of meeting
[normal] the UK 
[normal]2050 
[normal]decarbonisation 
[normal]target
[normal] set out in the Climate Change Act 2008
[normal]. 
[normal]These scenarios 
[normal]vary greatly in terms
[normal] of 
[normal]the development of electricity generation capacity using CCS
[normal]. Coal CCS 
[normal]ranges
[normal] from 0 to 38 
[normal]gigawatts (GW)
[normal], gas CCS 
[normal]ranges 
[normal]from 0 to 2.3 GW, co-
[normal]firing 
[normal]is 
[normal]up to 51 GW
[normal],
[normal] and biomass CCS 
[normal]is 
[normal]up to 5 GW.
[normal] Wh
[normal]ile the
[normal] combination of CCS sources (gas, coal, co-fir
[normal]ing or biomass) varies 
[normal]significantly 
[normal]between
[normal] scenario
[normal]s
[normal], all 
[normal]of them 
[normal]include at least some CCS 
[normal]capacity
[normal]. 
[normal]The scenario with the lowest CCS capacity
[normal] 
[normal]estimates at least 12 GW will be in operation by 2050. The 
[normal]scenario with the 
[normal]highest 
[normal]capacity 
[normal]envisages up to 
[normal]57 GW.
[normal] Overall, CCS is expected to 
[normal]meet 
[normal]between 12 
[normal]and 
[normal]37 per cent of total electricity demand in 2050.
[normal]15.
[normal]              
[normal]Nevertheless, considerable work remains to demonstrate CCS at large scale and across 
[normal]all of its stages
[normal],
[normal] both for power generation and for 
[normal]application to 
[normal]other industrial sectors.
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]idespread deployment is unlikely 
[normal]before 
[normal]2020
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]b
[normal]y 
[normal]which time capacity could
[normal] range between 1.5 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]5
[normal].0
[normal] GW (LCICG, 2012)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]16.
[normal]              
[normal]According to the Low Carbon Innovation Coordination Group (LCICG, 2012)
[normal], the areas of
[normal] innovation
[normal] 
[normal]which could provide
[normal] the biggest 
[normal]potential 
[normal]benefit
[normal]s
[normal] to t
[normal]he UK are (i) deep sea storage 
[normal]and
[normal] related monitoring;
[normal] and (ii) advanced capture development (especially gas and biomass) and demonstration of integrated conversion-capture. There is also a case for broad support for leading ideas with 
[normal]‘
[normal]breakthrough
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]potential
[normal], such a
[normal]s
[normal] novel capture or com
[normal]pression concepts.
[normal]17.
[normal]              
[normal]CCS development in the UK
[normal] could be worth 
[normal]between 
[normal]4
[normal] per cent and 
[normal]6 per cent
[normal] share of the global CCS
[normal] market
[normal],
[normal] with potential cumulative gross 
[normal]added value
[normal] of b
[normal]etween £150
[normal] billion
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]£
[normal]750
[normal] billion
[normal] 
[normal]up to 2050, contributing 
[normal]between
[normal] £3 
[normal]billi
[normal]on and
[normal] 
[normal]£
[normal]16
[normal] billion
[normal] to UK GDP 
[normal](LCICG, 2012)
