[normal] advantage
[normal]s.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]45.
[normal]              
[normal]As the 
[normal]Select 
[normal]Committee ha
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]recognised, CCS has the potential to play a major role in the global effort to combat climate change. In 
[normal]its
[normal] low
[normal]-
[normal]carbon energy scenario (2 Degrees case)
[normal],
[normal] the 
[normal]International Energy Agency
[normal] 
[normal](2012a) 
[normal]show
[normal]s
[normal] CCS as the technology with the greatest potential for 
[normal]re
[normal]ducing carbon dioxide emissions
[normal]. CCS 
[normal]would 
[normal]account for 22 per cent
[normal] of 
[normal]reductions,
[normal] 
[normal]or 2.5 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide (equivalent to m
[normal]ore than two
[normal]-
[normal]thi
[normal]rds of Europe’s emissions today)
[normal]. This makes CCS a genuinely strategic option for global climate 
[normal]chang
[normal]e 
[normal]mitigation.
[normal]46.
[normal]              
[normal]Although the 
[normal]viability of the 
[normal]component technologies ha
[normal]s
[normal] been demonstrated
[normal],
[normal] there are many uncertainties, as described above, about 
[normal]the
[normal] technical and commercial implementation
[normal] 
[normal]of CCS at a 
[normal]large scale
[normal]. The UK still has significant advantages in terms of well
[normal]-
[normal]understood offshore reservoirs where 
[normal]carbon dioxide
[normal] could be stored, a strong oil and gas sector with relevant expertise, and 
[normal]a capable engineering and research base. While i
[normal]nvestment
[normal] in CCS 
[normal]faces 
[normal]a
[normal] number of policy, legal and insurance challenges, 
[normal]this
[normal] 
[normal]is 
[normal]a key
[normal] climate 
[normal]change 
